raphical -- t15. The Search for the Lost Parent in Joy Kogawa’s Obasan and Ene Mihkelson’s Ahasveeruse uni (The Sleep of Ahasuerus) -- t16. Making the Silence Speak: A Critical Discussion of Trauma Transmission and Identity Formation -- tPart Four: Fictions of Loss and Trauma -- t17. (Re-)Visions of the Buried Self: Childhood Trauma and Self-Narration in Margaret Atwood’s Cat’s Eye -- t18. Grasping Patterns of Violence -- t19. Nostalgia and Redemption in Bernard Kangro’s Joonatan Novels -- t20. Renegotiations of Longing and Belonging: Exile, Memory, and Nostalgia -- t21. Haunted Whispers from the Footnotes: Life Writing in Raj Kamal Jha’s Fireproof -- t22. What Only Fiction Can Do -- tAfterword: Ethical and Political Aspects of Life Writing and Remembering -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExploring life writing from a variety of cultural contexts, Haunted Narratives provides new insights into how individuals and communities across time and space deal with traumatic experiences and haunting memories. From the perspectives of trauma theory, memory studies, gender studies, literary studies, philosophy, and post-colonial studies, the volume stresses the lingering, haunting presence of the past in the present. The contributors focus on the psychological, ethical, and representational difficulties involved in narrative negotiations of traumatic memories.Haunted Narratives focuses on life writing in the broadest sense of the term: biographies and autobiographies that deal with traumatic experiences, autobiographically inspired fictions on loss and trauma, and limit-cases that transcend clear-cut distinctions between the factual and the fictional. In discussing texts as diverse as Toni Morrison’s Beloved, Vikram Seth’s Two Lives, deportation narratives of Baltic women, Christa Wolf’s Kindheitsmuster, Joy Kogawa’s Obasan, and Ene Mihkelson’s Ahasveeruse uni, the 